In Kubernetes, Soft Node Affinity is essentially a "nice-to-have" request for the scheduler.
While hard affinity says, "You must run me on this specific type of node or don't run me at all," soft affinity says, "I would prefer to run on this type of node, but if none are available or they are all full, just put me anywhere so I can get to work."
In the YAML configuration, this is defined under the lengthy field: preferredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution.
How Soft Affinity Works: Weights and Scoring
When you use soft affinity, you can specify multiple preferences and assign a weight between 1 and 100 to each one.
The Kubernetes scheduler uses these weights to score nodes:
	1	The scheduler looks at all nodes that meet your basic resource requirements (CPU, memory).
	2	For each node, it checks your soft affinity rules. If a node matches a rule, the scheduler adds that rule's weight to the node's total score.
	3	The node with the highest final score wins and gets the pod.
A Practical Example
Imagine you have a web application. You want it to run on nodes with high-performance SSDs (disktype=ssd) for faster caching, but you don't want the app to crash or stay pending if all the SSD nodes are busy.
Here is how you write that manifest:
YAML




apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: web-app-preferred
spec:
  containers:
  - name: web-server
    image: nginx:latest
  affinity:
    nodeAffinity:
      preferredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution:
      - weight: 80
        preference:
          matchExpressions:
          - key: disktype
            operator: In
            values:
            - ssd
Why use a weight like 80?
If you have multiple preferences, weights allow you to prioritize them. For example:
	•	Preference 1: Node has an SSD (weight: 80)
	•	Preference 2: Node is in availability zone us-east-1a (weight: 20)
A node that has an SSD and is in us-east-1a will get a score boost of 100. A node that only has an SSD gets 80. If a node has no SSD but is in us-east-1a, it gets 20. The scheduler will naturally pick the best match available.
When should you use Soft Affinity?
	•	Cost Optimization: Preferring spot instances or cheaper node groups for non-critical background workers, but falling back to on-demand nodes if spot capacity runs out.
	•	Zonal/Regional Distribution: Preferring to keep microservices in the same availability zone to reduce network latency and cross-zone data traffic costs, while allowing cross-zone scheduling if a zone goes down.
	•	Hardware Upgrades: Preferring newer generation CPU/architecture nodes (instance-type=m6i) but allowing deployment on older nodes (instance-type=m5) if the cluster is tightly packed.



The reason Pod Affinity keeps nodeSelectorTerms (or rather, a very similar list structure) even in its soft flavor is because of how Pod Affinity calculates boundaries.
It comes down to a fundamental difference in what the two features are searching for:
	•	Node Affinity looks at Nodes (which are single, flat objects).
	•	Pod Affinity looks at Pods matching specific criteria across complex topological boundaries (like nodes, zones, or regions).
Because Pod Affinity has to do a lot more logical heavy lifting, its soft affinity structure requires a list wrapper called podAffinityTerm.
Let's look at the syntax difference side-by-side to see why it's there.
Side-by-Side: Soft Node vs. Soft Pod Affinity
Notice how the structure changes when you switch from targeting a node to targeting a pod:
1. Soft Node Affinity (No extra wrapper)
YAML


      preferredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution:
      - weight: 80
        preference: # <-- Straight into the matching rule
          matchExpressions:
          - key: disktype
            operator: In
            values:
            - ssd
2. Soft Pod Affinity (Uses podAffinityTerm)
YAML

      preferredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution:
      - weight: 80
        podAffinityTerm: # <-- The wrapper returns!
          labelSelector: # <-- Required to find the right pod
            matchExpressions:
            - key: security
              operator: In
              values:
              - S1
          topologyKey: topology.kubernetes.io/zone # <-- Required boundary
Why does Soft Pod Affinity need that extra wrapper?
Soft Node Affinity only needs to know one thing: the node label.
Soft Pod Affinity needs to bundle two completely different pieces of information together for the preference to make sense:
	1	labelSelector: Which pods are we looking for? (e.g., "Find pods labeled security=S1").
	2	topologyKey: What is the geographic boundary we are trying to match? (e.g., "Keep us in the same availability zone").
Because Kubernetes needs to pair that specific labelSelector to that exact topologyKey as a single unit, it wraps them together inside a podAffinityTerm.
If it didn't use a wrapper, you wouldn't be able to define multiple complex preferences cleanly (for example: preferring to be on the same hostname as Pod A, while also preferring to be in the same zone as Pod B).
